'''Joan Elise Robinson Acker'''<ref name=Congress>{{cite web |title= Acker, Joan |url= http://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/n87874062.html |publisher= Library of Congress |accessdate= 4 January 2015 |quote= (Joan Elise Robinson Acker) vita (b. 1924) }}</ref> (March 18, 1924{{snd}}June 22, 2016) was an American sociologist, researcher, writer, and educator. She was a part of the [[University of Oregon]] faculty since 1967.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Joan Acker {{!}} Department of Sociology|url = http://sociology.uoregon.edu/profile/jacker/|website = sociology.uoregon.edu|accessdate = 2015-11-23}}</ref> Acker is considered one of the leading analysts regarding gender and class within the [[Second-wave feminism|second wave of feminism.]]<ref>{{Cite web|title = Joan Acker's Feminist Historical-Materialist Theory of Class|url = http://monthlyreview.org/2012/06/01/joan-ackers-feminist-historical-materialist-theory-of-class/|website = Monthly Review|accessdate = 2015-11-23|first = John Bellamy Foster Topics:|last = Feminism}}</ref>

== Education ==
Acker was born in Illinois in 1924.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=q7KZAAAAIAAJ&q=%22Acker,+joan%22+1924&dq=%22Acker,+joan%22+1924&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjkzszm-77NAhXJ8x4KHcrLDjwQ6AEIMjAE]</ref> She received her bachelors from [[Hunter College]], her master's from the [[University of Chicago]], and her Ph.D. from the [[University of Oregon]].<ref name="Love2006">{{cite book|author=Barbara J. Love|title=Feminists who changed America, 1963-1975|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kpNarH7t9CkC|accessdate=4 January 2012|year=2006|publisher=University of Illinois Press|isbn=978-0-252-03189-2|page=4}}</ref>

== Career ==
Acker is best known for her theories on the relationship between race, class, and gender. She discusses this relationship in several of her publications, including her 2006 book ''[[Class Questions: Feminist Answers]]''.<ref>{{Cite journal|url = |title = Class Questions, Feminist Answers|last = Williams|first = Christine|date = April 2007|journal = Gender & Society|doi = 10.1177/0891243206295784|pmid = |issue = 2|volume = 21|pages = 302–304}}</ref> Acker describes the need to think about race, class, and gender not as separate entities but as "intersecting systems of oppression.<ref>{{Cite journal|url = |title = Class Questions: Feminist Answers|last = Anderson|first = Margaret|date = May 2007|journal = Contemporary Sociology|doi = |pmid = |publisher = American Sociological Association|volume = 36|issue = 3|pages = 234–235}}</ref> In 1973, Acker founded the [[Center for the Study of Women in Society]] at the University of Oregon. She successfully helped to raise pay wages for low-wage jobs in Oregon while serving on a state task force from 1981-1983.<ref name=Love2006 /> She received the [[American Sociological Association]]'s Career of Distinguished Scholarship Award in 1993.<ref>{{Cite web|title = American Sociological Association: W.E.B. DuBois Career of Distinguished Scholarship Award|url = http://www.asanet.org/about/awards/duboiscareer.cfm|website = www.asanet.org|accessdate = 2015-11-23|deadurl = yes|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20151120100928/http://www.asanet.org/about/awards/duboiscareer.cfm|archivedate = 2015-11-20|df = }}</ref> In 1989, Acker was also awarded the [[Jessie Bernard Award]] for feminist scholarship.<ref>{{Cite web|title = American Sociological Association: Jessie Bernard Award|url = http://www.asanet.org/about/awards/bernard.cfm|website = www.asanet.org|accessdate = 2015-11-23}}</ref> She died on June 22, 2016 at the age of 92.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://csws.uoregon.edu/memory-joan-acker-1924-2016/ | title=In Memory of Joan Acker: 1924 – 2016 | accessdate=23 June 2016}}</ref>

