{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2017}} {{Infobox person | name = Michael Lieber | image = | caption= | birth_name = Michael John Griffiths | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1988|5|6|df=yes}} | birth_place = [[Tenby]], [[South Wales]] | occupation = Actor, Author | height = 1.8 m | education = [[Maple Hayes]], [[Oxford School of Drama|Oxford School of Speech and Drama]] | years_active = 1998–present | signature = Michael Lieber Signature.png }}
'''Michael Lieber''' is a [[United Kingdom|British]] stage and screen actor known for playing the real life mathematician [[John E. Littlewood]] in the 2014 [[biopic]] [[period drama]] '[[Ramanujan (film)|Ramanujan]]' and his disturbing performance as Mark Crowe in the dark thriller '[[A Room To Die For]]' produced by [[Sony Pictures]].
==Career==
===Early life=== Lieber was born in [[Tenby]], [[South Wales]] on May 6, 1988.<ref name="Gulf News">{{cite news |url=http://gulfnews.com/life-style/celebrity/desi-news/south-india/meet-the-british-stars-of-ramanujan-1.1357486| title=Meet the British stars of ‘Ramanujan’| work=[[Gulf News]] | date=May 24, 2017| author=Mythily Ramachandran}}</ref> He began performing at aged 10 as a busker and street magician in Wales before moving to England to attended [[Maple Hayes|Maple Hayes School for Dyslexics]] from (1999-2004),<ref name="Lichfield Mercury">{{cite news |url=http://www.lichfieldmercury.co.uk/lichfield-actor-wraps-filming-new-horror-movie/story-26673767-detail/story.html| title=Lichfield actor wraps filming on new horror movie| work=[[Lichfield Mercury]] | date=June 12, 2015| author=Alex Keller}}</ref> and studied drama at [[Oxford School of Drama|The Oxford School of Speech and Drama]] from 2006 to 2008. He moved to [[London]] in 2009 and performed in a number of theatre productions from 2009 to 2012, the most notable being ''Before Nell'',<ref name="Deccan Herald">{{cite news | url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/361496/039i-like-play-sinister-characters039.html| title='I like to play sinister characters'| work=[[Deccan Herald]] | date=Oct 7, 2013| author=Anupama Ramakrishnan}}</ref> a one-man show about one of Shakespeare's own players in the 16th century who has spent his life performing as a woman and reveals a horrific life story of sickness, prostitution and war. Lieber lost two stone to play the part and performed it in a red silk gown, the show won him a theatrical agent and a handful of complementary reviews from London critics.
===Film=== His first break in film came in 2013 when the [[Tamil language|Tamil]] director [[Gnana Rajasekaran]] started production on his new biopic [[Ramanujan (film)|Ramanujan]], a period drama set in 1914 about the life and untimely death of the prodigy Cambridge mathematician [[Srinivasa Ramanujan]], the movie was the first of its kind a bilingual collaboration shot back to back in both English and Tamil. Michael was cast as the real life play-boy mathematician John E. Littlewood starring alongside Kevin Mcgowan, [[Cloudia Swann]], and [[Richard Walsh (actor)|Richard Walsh]],<ref name="The Hindu">{{cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-metroplus/faces-and-facts/article5411744.ece| title=Faces and facts| work=[[The Hindu]] | date=December 2, 2013| author=Harshikaa Udasi}}</ref> When preparing to play the part Lieber tracked down one of the only people still alive to have worked with Littlewood, the renowned Romanian Mathematician professor [[Béla Bollobás]].<ref name="The Pioneer">{{cite news |url=http://www.dailypioneer.com/vivacity/date-with-digits.html| title=DATE WITH DIGITS’| work=[[The Pioneer (newspaper)|The Pioneer]] | date=October 3, 2013| author=Iknoor Kaur}}</ref>
In 2017 he played the lead role of Mark Crowe in Devanand Shanmugam psychological [[Thriller film|thriller]] [[A Room To Die For]]<ref name="Britflicks">{{cite news |url=http://www.britflicks.com/blog.aspx?blogid=17659| title=Michael Lieber Talks About His Role In UK Horror A ROOM TO DIE FOR (aka RANCOUR) ’| work=Britflicks | date= May 18, 2015}}</ref> produced by [[Sony Pictures]], alongside [[Lock, Stock and Two Smoking Barrels]] star [[Vas Blackwood]].
===Theatre===
In 2010, he starred as the crazy eyed over-the-hill footballer Ray Keane in Matthew J. Gunn's dark comedy play Transfer Deadline Day at the [[Courtyard Theatre, London|Courtyard Theater]], London, England.<ref name="Remotegoat">{{cite news |url=https://www.remotegoat.com/uk/review/5344/a-game-of-few-laughs/| title=A game of few laughs| work=[[Remotegoat]] | date= May 26, 2010 | author=Andy Slater }}</ref>
