'''Oceanus Hopkins''' (1620{{mdash}}{{circa}}1626) was the only child born on the ''[[Mayflower]]''<ref name="mayflowerhistory">{{cite web|title=Oceanus Hopkins|url=http://mayflowerhistory.com/hopkins-oceanus/|website=MayflowerHistory.com|publisher=MayflowerHistory.com|accessdate=12 July 2016|ref=mayflowerhistory}}</ref> during its historic voyage which brought the [[Kingdom of England|English]] [[Separatism#Religious separatism|Pilgrims]] to [[United States|America]]. A boy, [[Peregrine White]], was born on board, after arriving in America, as the ship lay at anchor.
Oceanus was born to [[Stephen Hopkins (Mayflower passenger)|Stephen Hopkins]] and his wife, [[Elizabeth Hopkins]] (née Fisher),<ref name="ISTG">{{cite web|title=Immigrant Ships Transcribers Guild|url=http://www.immigrantships.net/v2/1600v2/mayflower16201111.html|website=ISTG|publisher=ISTG™Immigrant Ships Transcribers Guild LLC|accessdate=12 July 2016|ref=ISTG}}</ref> sometime between the boarding and arrival dates of September 6 and November 9, 1620. He died at about age six, certainly before the [[Plymouth Colony#Economy|1627 Division of Cattle]].<ref>Rod Gragg, ''The Pilgrim Chronicles: An Eyewitness History of the Pilgrims and the Founding of Plymouth Colony'', 2014, {{ISBN|1621572692}}, p. 294</ref> The location of his grave is unknown.
He was named 'Oceanus', [[Latin]] for 'ocean', because he was born on the [[Atlantic Ocean]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.tn/books?id=EU28BAAAQBAJ&pg=PP6&lpg=PP6&dq='the+kid+was+called+Oceanus+because+he+was+born+on+the+Atlantic+Ocean.&source=bl&ots=8bdlJwDA5u&sig=8IPttlHnJ77pm1WO8XLw7o85_Xo&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q='the%20kid%20was%20called%20Oceanus%20because%20he%20was%20born%20on%20the%20Atlantic%20Ocean.&f=false|title=American History (According to Roaches): The First Thanksgiving was Inspired by Roaches|last=Hatch|first=Ansel|date=2014-10-08|publisher=Ansel Hatch|isbn=9781311440648|language=en}}</ref>
==References== {{reflist}}
